<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Dot Product</h1>=20


<p>A <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/vectors.html">vector</a>=
 has <b>magnitude</b> (how long it is) and <b>direction</b>:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/v=
ector-mag-dir.svg" alt=3D"vector magnitude and direction" height=3D"137" wi=
dth=3D"267"></p>=20
<p>Here  are two vectors:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/v=
ectors.svg" alt=3D"vectors" height=3D"102" width=3D"154"></p>=20
<p>They can be <b>multiplied</b> using the "<b>Dot Product</b>" (also see <=
a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/vectors-cross-product.html">Cr=
oss Product</a>).</p>=20


<h2>Calculating</h2>=20

<p>The Dot Product is written using a central dot:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"larger"><b>a</b> =C2=B7 <b>b</b></span><=
br>
This means the Dot Product of <b>a</b> and <b>b</b></p>=20
<p>We can calculate the Dot Product of two vectors this way:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D |<b>a</b>| =C3=97 |<b>b</b=
>| =C3=97 cos(=CE=B8)</p>=20
<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
dot-product-1.svg" alt=3D"dot product magnitudes and angle" height=3D"132" =
width=3D"155"></p>=20
<p>Where:<br>
|<b>a</b>| is the magnitude (length) of vector <b>a</b><br>
|<b>b</b>| is the magnitude (length) of vector <b>b<br>
</b>   =CE=B8 is the angle between <b>a</b> and <b>b</b></p>=20
<p>So we multiply the length of <b>a</b> times  the length of <b>b</b>, the=
n multiply by the cosine of the angle between <b>a</b> and <b>b</b></p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>OR we can calculate it this way:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D a<sub>x</sub> =C3=97 b<sub=
>x</sub> + a<sub>y</sub> =C3=97 b<sub>y</sub></p>=20
<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
dot-product-2.svg" alt=3D"dot product components" height=3D"146" width=3D"1=
63"></p>=20
<p>So we multiply the x's, multiply the y's, then add.</p>=20
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>
<p class=3D"center large">Both methods work!</p>=20
<p>And the result is a <b>number</b> (called a "scalar" to show it is not a=
 vector).</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Calculate the dot product of  vectors <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>:<=
/h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
dot-product-ex1.gif" alt=3D"dot product example" height=3D"202" width=3D"21=
4"></p>=20
	<p><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D |<b>a</b>| =C3=97 |<b>b</b>| =C3=97 cos(=CE=B8)</=
p>=20
	<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 10 =C3=97 13 =C3=97 cos(59,5=C2=B0=
)</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 10 =C3=97 13 =C3=97 0,5075...</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 65,98... =3D 66 (rounded)</div>
<p>OR we can calculate it this way:</p>=20
<p><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D a<sub>x</sub> =C3=97 b<sub>x</sub> + a<sub>y</sub>=
 =C3=97 b<sub>y</sub></p>=20
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D -6 =C3=97 5 + 8 =C3=97 12</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D -30 + 96</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 66</div>
<p>Both methods came up with the same result (after rounding)</p>=20
<p>Also note that we used <b>minus 6</b> for a<sub>x</sub> (it is heading i=
n the negative x-direction)</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Note: you can use the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/vect=
or-calculator.html">Vector Calculator</a> to help you.</p>=20


<h2>Why cos(=CE=B8) ?</h2>=20

<p>OK, to multiply two vectors it makes sense to multiply their lengths tog=
ether <i><b>but only when they point in the same direction</b></i><b>.</b><=
/p>=20
<p>So we make one  "point in the same direction" as the other by multiplyin=
g by cos(=CE=B8):</p>


<div class=3D"center">
	<div class=3D"box" style=3D"vertical-align: bottom;"><img src=3D"https://w=
ww.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/dot-product-a-cos.svg" alt=3D"dot product =
|a| cos(theta)" height=3D"131" width=3D"144"><br>We take the component of <=
b>a</b><br>
	that lies alongside <b>b</b></div>
	<div class=3D"box"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/d=
ot-product-light.svg" alt=3D"dot product shine light" height=3D"245" width=
=3D"176"><br>Like shining a light to see<br>
	where the shadow lies</div>
</div>


<p class=3D"large">THEN we multiply !</p>

<div class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/image=
s/dot-product-b-cos.svg" alt=3D"dot product |b| cos(theta)"></div>
<p>It works exactly the same if we "projected" <b>b</b> alongside <b>a</b> =
then multiplied.</p>=20
<p>Because it doesn't matter which order we do the multiplication:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">|<b>a</b>| =C3=97 <span class=3D"hilite">|<b>b</=
b>| =C3=97 cos(=CE=B8)</span> =3D <span class=3D"hilite">|<b>a</b>|  =C3=97=
 cos(=CE=B8)</span> =C3=97 |<b>b</b>|</p>

<p class=3D"center large">In effect, the dot product multiplies the <b>alig=
ned</b> lengths.</p>=20

<h3>Remembering Cos</h3>
<p>To remember to multiply by cos(=CE=B8) think <span class=3D"larger">"dot=
 cos"</span>.</p>
<h2>Right Angles</h2>=20

<p>When two vectors are at right angles to each other the dot product is <b=
>zero</b>.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: calculate the dot product for:</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
dot-product-right-angle.svg" alt=3D"dot product right angle"></p>=20
	<p><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D |<b>a</b>| =C3=97 |<b>b</b>| =C3=97 cos(=CE=B8)</=
p>=20
	<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D |<b>a</b>| =C3=97 |<b>b</b>| =C3=
=97 cos(90=C2=B0)</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D |<b>a</b>| =C3=97 |<b>b</b>| =C3=97=
 0</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 0</div>
<p>or we can calculate it this way:</p>=20
<p><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D a<sub>x</sub> =C3=97 b<sub>x</sub> + a<sub>y</sub>=
 =C3=97 b<sub>y</sub></p>=20
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D -12 =C3=97 12 + 16 =C3=97 9</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D -144 + 144</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 0</div>
</div>=20

<p>This can be a handy way to find out if two vectors are at right angles.<=
/p>=20

<h2>Same Direction</h2>

<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/d=
ot-product-aligned.svg" alt=3D"aligned vectors"></p>=20

<p>The dot product of two vectors that point in the same direction is the s=
imple product of their lengths, because the angle is 0 degrees which has a =
cosine of 1</p>

<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D |<b>a</b>| =C3=97 |<b>b</b>| =C3=97=
 cos(0=C2=B0)</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D a =C3=97 b =C3=97 1</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D ab</div>


<h2>Right-Angled Triangle</h2>

<p>Let's use the dot product on a right-angled triangle!</p>

<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/v=
ector-pythagoras.svg" alt=3D"pythagoras theorem as vectors"></p>=20

<div class=3D"two">
	<div class=3D"lt">Vector <b>c</b> is the sum of <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>:</di=
v>
	<div class=3D"rt"><b>c</b> =3D <b>a</b> + <b>b</b></div>
	<div class=3D"lt">Do a dot product on both sides:</div>
	<div class=3D"rt"><b>c =C2=B7 c</b> =3D (<b>a</b> + <b>b</b>) =C2=B7  (<b>=
a</b> + <b>b</b>)</div>
	<div class=3D"lt">Expand:</div>
	<div class=3D"rt"><b>c =C2=B7 c</b> =3D <b>a</b> =C2=B7  (<b>a</b> + <b>b<=
/b>) + <b>b</b> =C2=B7 (<b>a</b> + <b>b</b>)</div>
	<div class=3D"lt">Expand Again:</div>
	<div class=3D"rt"><b>c =C2=B7 c</b> =3D <b>a</b> =C2=B7  <b>a</b> +  <b>a<=
/b> =C2=B7  <b>b</b> + <b>b</b> =C2=B7 <b>a</b> + <b>b</b> =C2=B7 <b>b</b><=
/div>
	<div class=3D"lt"><b>a</b> =C2=B7 <b>b</b> =3D <b>b</b> =C2=B7 <b>a</b> =
=3D 0 (right angles):</div>
	<div class=3D"rt"><b>c =C2=B7 c</b> =3D <b>a</b> =C2=B7  <b>a</b> + <b>b</=
b> =C2=B7 <b>b</b></div>
	<div class=3D"lt"><b>c</b> =C2=B7 <b>c</b> =3D c<sup>2</sup> etc:</div>
	<div class=3D"rt">c<sup>2</sup> =3D a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup></div>
</div>
<p class=3D"large">We just proved the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com=
/pythagoras.html">Pythagorean Theorem</a>!</p>
<p>Note: when we allow angles other than 90 degrees we can create the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/trig-cosine-law.html">Law of Cosin=
es</a>. Have a go yourself, but be careful how you define the angle!</p>

<h2>Physics</h2>=20

<p>The Dot Product is used a lot in Physics</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Work</h3>=20

	<p>In Physics <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/physics/energy-work.ht=
ml">Work</a> is force times distance, but only the <b>aligned</b> part.</p>=
=20
	<p>So work is the dot product of force and distance.</p>=20
	<p>Alex pushes a&nbsp;box 3 m straight forward using 200 N of force. But h=
is  push is a little upwards by 20=C2=B0.</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/physics/images/=
push-box-20.svg" alt=3D"push box 20 degrees" height=3D"117" width=3D"372"><=
/p>=20
	<div class=3D"two">=20
	<div class=3D"lt">Work =3D</div>
<div class=3D"rt"><b>Force</b> =C2=B7 <b>Distance</b></div>
<div class=3D"lt">=3D</div>
<div class=3D"rt"><b>Force</b> =C3=97 <b>Distance</b> =C3=97 cos =CE=B8</di=
v>
<div class=3D"lt">=3D</div>
<div class=3D"rt"><b>200 N</b> =C3=97 <b>3 m</b>  =C3=97 cos 20=C2=B0</div>
<div class=3D"lt">=3D</div>
<div class=3D"rt"><b>200 N</b> =C3=97 <b>3 m</b> =C3=97 0,9397...</div>
<div class=3D"lt">=3D</div>
<div class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"larger">564 J</span> (to nearest Joule, wh=
ere J =3D N m)</div>
</div>   =20

<p>(Without cos =CE=B8, the <i><b>wrong</b></i> value would be 600 J)</p>=
=20
</div>=20


<h2>Three or More Dimensions</h2>=20

<p>This all works fine in 3 (or more) dimensions, too.</p>=20
<p>And can actually be very useful!</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Sam has measured the end-points of two poles, and wants to kn=
ow <b>the angle between them</b>:</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
dot-product-ex2.gif" alt=3D"dot product 3d" height=3D"261" width=3D"317"></=
p>=20
	<p>We have 3 dimensions, so don't forget the z-components:</p>=20
	<p><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D a<sub>x</sub> =C3=97 b<sub>x</sub> + a<sub>y</sub=
> =C3=97 b<sub>y</sub> + a<sub>z</sub> =C3=97 b<sub>z</sub></p>=20
	<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 9 =C3=97 4 + 2 =C3=97 8  + 7 =C3=
=97 10</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 36 + 16 + 70</div>
<div class=3D"so"><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 122</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>Now for the other formula:</p>=20
<p><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D |<b>a</b>| =C3=97 |<b>b</b>| =C3=97 cos(=CE=B8)</p=
>=20
<p>But what is |<b>a</b>| ? It is the magnitude, or length, of the vector <=
b>a</b>. We can use <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/pythagoras.html">=
Pythagoras</a>:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>|<b>a</b>| =3D =E2=88=9A(4<sup>2</sup> + 8<sup>2</sup> + 10<sup>2</sup=
>)</li>=20
	<li>|<b>a</b>| =3D  =E2=88=9A(16 + 64 + 100)</li>=20
	<li>|<b>a</b>| =3D   =E2=88=9A180</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Likewise for |<b>b</b>|:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>|<b>b</b>| =3D =E2=88=9A(9<sup>2</sup> + 2<sup>2</sup> + 7<sup>2</sup>=
)</li>=20
	<li>|<b>b</b>| =3D  =E2=88=9A(81 + 4 + 49)</li>=20
	<li>|<b>b</b>| =3D   =E2=88=9A134</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>And we know from the calculation above that <b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D 122, s=
o:</p>=20
<p><b>a =C2=B7 b</b> =3D |<b>a</b>| =C3=97 |<b>b</b>| =C3=97 cos(=CE=B8)</p=
>=20
<div class=3D"so">122 =3D =E2=88=9A180 =C3=97 =E2=88=9A134 =C3=97 cos(=CE=
=B8)</div>
<div class=3D"so">cos(=CE=B8) =3D 122 / (=E2=88=9A180 =C3=97 =E2=88=9A134)<=
/div>
<div class=3D"so">cos(=CE=B8) =3D 0,7855...</div>
<div class=3D"so">=CE=B8 =3D cos<sup>-1</sup>(0,7855...) =3D 38,2...=C2=B0<=
/div>
<p>Done!</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>I tried a calculation like that once, but worked all in angles and dista=
nces ... it was very hard, involved lots of trigonometry, and my brain hurt=
. The method above is much easier.</p>=20


<h2>Cross Product</h2>=20

<p>The Dot Product gives  a <b>scalar</b> (ordinary number)  answer, and is=
 sometimes called the <b>scalar product</b>.</p>=20
<p>But there is also the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/vect=
ors-cross-product.html">Cross Product</a> which gives a <b>vector</b> as an=
 answer, and is sometimes called the <b>vector product</b>.</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
